So, if both user1.c and user2.c needs the same variable (not a good idea) or the same function, then they need to be "defined" in a .h file but only declared in one of them.

e.g
```
---- user.h ----

extern int my_bad_global_variable;
void my_function();

---- user1.c ----

int my_bad_global_variable;

void my_function() { ... }

---- user2.c ----
#include "user.h"

void main() {
  if( my_bad_global_variable )
    my_function();
}
```

@Niclas Here it is. Please excuse the garbled spaghetti code. It's been copy and pasted between the IDE and Notepad a few times so it has lost its formatting along the way. It's also just garbage code in general so I truly apologize if it's an eye sore. 

The basic gist is that I am going to be sending audio data from a buffer called audioRxBuffer to the Pi over SPI. I am trying to send via DMA because I have to send at a sampling rate of 44.1 KHz, which is 44,100 samples per second over 8 channels. Because of how large this is, it's split into buffers of 4096 samples that I will be sending at any one moment of time. The data itself is floats, so 32 bits, so I need to send 4096 * 4 = 16,384 bytes in a moment. Now because this 44.1 KHz is split into buffers, these buffers have to send in a hundredth of a second. Basically, I have to send 44,100 / 4096 = 11 buffers a second (where each buffer has 16,384 bytes). 

After doing the math, this is approximately 1.4 Megabytes per second. So, I set my clock speed on both the STM and the Pi to 20 MHz to account for this and decided to use DMA for such a large data transfer.

So, the CubeMX will generate this bit of code in `stm32f4xx_it.c`:
```
/**
  * @brief This function handles UART4 global interrupt.
  */
void UART4_IRQHandler(void)
{
  /* USER CODE BEGIN UART4_IRQn 0 */

  /* USER CODE END UART4_IRQn 0 */
  HAL_UART_IRQHandler(&huart4);
  /* USER CODE BEGIN UART4_IRQn 1 */

  /* USER CODE END UART4_IRQn 1 */
}
```

Looking at that IRQ handler it will do a LOT of error checking and such, but it will end with:

```
#if (USE_HAL_UART_REGISTER_CALLBACKS == 1)
        /*Call registered Rx Event callback*/
        huart->RxEventCallback(huart, (huart->RxXferSize - huart->RxXferCount));
#else
        /*Call legacy weak Rx Event callback*/
        HAL_UARTEx_RxEventCallback(huart, (huart->RxXferSize - huart->RxXferCount));
#endif /* USE_HAL_UART_REGISTER_CALLBACKS */
```

As I said - either calling the registered one or the default global one.
